const QUIZ_QUESTIONS = [{"id":1,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of the king who held a great feast in Esther chapter 1?","options":["King Darius","King Ahasuerus","King Nebuchadnezzar","King Cyrus"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 1:1-3","explanation":"King Ahasuerus (also known as Xerxes) reigned from India to Ethiopia over 127 provinces. He made a feast for all his officials and servants in the third year of his reign. That's a LOT of provinces to rule!"},{"id":2,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"How many days did King Ahasuerus's great feast last?","options":["7 days","30 days","180 days","365 days"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 1:4","explanation":"The king showed the riches of his glorious kingdom for 180 days — that's about 6 months! After that, he made another feast for 7 days. Talk about a long party!"},{"id":3,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"Why was Queen Vashti removed from her position?","options":["She stole from the treasury","She refused to come when the king summoned her","She plotted against the king","She left the kingdom"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 1:10-12","explanation":"Queen Vashti refused to come when King Ahasuerus commanded her to appear before his guests wearing the royal crown, to show her beauty. The king was furious, and his advisors said she should be removed so other women wouldn't follow her example."},{"id":4,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"Who was Esther's cousin who raised her as his own daughter?","options":["Haman","Mordecai","Hegai","Memucan"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 2:5-7","explanation":"Mordecai the son of Jair, of the tribe of Benjamin, had raised his cousin Esther (whose Hebrew name was Hadassah) because her father and mother had died. He brought her up as his own daughter — what an amazing guardian!"},{"id":5,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Esther's Hebrew name?","options":["Hadassah","Hannah","Huldah","Hagar"],"correct":0,"reference":"Esther 2:7","explanation":"Esther's Hebrew name was Hadassah, which means 'myrtle tree.' The name 'Esther' was likely her Persian name. She was described as lovely and beautiful!"},{"id":6,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"How long was the beauty preparation period before each young woman went to the king?","options":["6 months","12 months","3 months","18 months"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 2:12","explanation":"Each young woman had twelve months of beauty preparations — six months with oil of myrrh and six months with perfumes and preparations. That's a whole year of getting ready! Imagine spending a year just getting pampered!"},{"id":7,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of the man who hated Mordecai and plotted to destroy the Jews?","options":["Hegai","Memucan","Haman","Bigthana"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 3:5-6","explanation":"Haman the Agagite was furious because Mordecai would not bow down to him. Instead of just targeting Mordecai, Haman plotted to destroy ALL the Jews throughout the entire kingdom. His pride and hatred led to a terrible plan!"},{"id":8,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"Haman cast Pur (the lot) to determine the day to destroy the Jews. In which month was the destruction planned?","options":["The first month (Nisan)","The seventh month (Tishri)","The twelfth month (Adar)","The sixth month (Elul)"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 3:7,13","explanation":"The lot fell on the twelfth month, which is the month of Adar. Haman cast the lot in the first month (Nisan), so God actually gave the Jews almost a full year to prepare! The festival of Purim gets its name from 'Pur' meaning 'lot.'"},{"id":9,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What famous words did Mordecai say to Esther to encourage her to act?","options":["'Be strong and of good courage'","'The Lord is with you'","'Who knows whether you have come to the kingdom for such a time as this?'","'Trust in the Lord with all your heart'"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 4:14","explanation":"Mordecai's powerful words — 'who knows whether you have come to the kingdom for such a time as this?' — reminded Esther that God may have placed her in the palace for this very purpose: to save His people! It's one of the most famous verses in the Bible."},{"id":10,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"How many days did Esther ask the Jews to fast before she approached the king?","options":["1 day","3 days","7 days","40 days"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 4:16","explanation":"Esther asked all the Jews in Shushan to fast for three days, night and day. She and her maids would do the same. Then she would go to the king, even though it was against the law. Her famous words: 'If I perish, I perish!' What courage!"},{"id":11,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What happened when Esther approached the king without being summoned?","options":["She was thrown in prison","The king held out his golden scepter to her","The guards stopped her","The king was angry"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 5:2","explanation":"When the king saw Queen Esther standing in the court, she found favor in his sight, and the king held out the golden scepter that was in his hand. Esther drew near and touched the top of the scepter. God softened the king's heart!"},{"id":12,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Esther request at her first banquet with the king and Haman?","options":["She asked for Haman to be punished","She revealed that she was Jewish","She invited them to another banquet the next day","She asked the king to save her people"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 5:8","explanation":"Cleverly, Esther didn't rush! At the first banquet, she simply invited the king and Haman to come to ANOTHER banquet the next day. This built suspense and also set the stage for God to work overnight — because that very night, the king couldn't sleep!"},{"id":13,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Haman build at his house, planning to use it against Mordecai?","options":["A prison cell","A gallows fifty cubits high","A pit","A wall"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 5:14","explanation":"Haman's wife Zeresh and friends suggested he make a gallows fifty cubits high (about 75 feet!) and hang Mordecai on it. But God had other plans — Haman would end up on his own gallows! This is a perfect example of 'he who digs a pit will fall into it.'"},{"id":14,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What happened to the king on the night between Esther's two banquets?","options":["He had a dream about Mordecai","He could not sleep and had the book of records read to him","He received a warning from an angel","He became very ill"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 6:1","explanation":"That night the king could not sleep! So he commanded that the book of the records be brought, and it was found that Mordecai had saved the king's life by reporting a plot against him. The king realized Mordecai had never been rewarded. God's timing is perfect!"},{"id":15,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What humiliating thing did Haman have to do for Mordecai?","options":["Wash his feet","Lead him on horseback through the city proclaiming his honor","Bow down before him","Give him his house"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 6:10-11","explanation":"The king told Haman to put a royal robe and crown on Mordecai, place him on the king's horse, and lead him through the city square proclaiming 'Thus shall it be done to the man whom the king delights to honor!' Haman thought the king was talking about HIM — what a twist!"},{"id":16,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"At the second banquet, what did Esther reveal to the king?","options":["That she was from a royal family","That Mordecai was her father","That she and her people had been sold to be destroyed","That Haman had stolen from the treasury"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 7:3-4","explanation":"Esther bravely told the king: 'we have been sold, my people and I, to be destroyed, to be killed, and to be annihilated.' When the king asked who would dare do such a thing, Esther pointed to Haman: 'The adversary and enemy is this wicked Haman!'"},{"id":17,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What happened to Haman in the end?","options":["He was banished from the kingdom","He was hanged on the gallows he had prepared for Mordecai","He was thrown into prison","He escaped to another country"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 7:10","explanation":"Haman was hanged on the very gallows (50 cubits high!) that he had prepared for Mordecai. What a powerful example of God turning evil plans upside down! The Bible says: 'So they hanged Haman on the gallows that he had prepared for Mordecai. Then the king's wrath subsided.'"},{"id":18,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What position did Mordecai receive after Haman's downfall?","options":["He became a priest","He became captain of the guard","He was set over the house of Haman and became second to the king","He became governor of Judah"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 8:2, 10:3","explanation":"The king gave Mordecai the signet ring that he had taken from Haman, and Esther set Mordecai over the house of Haman. He became second only to King Ahasuerus, great among the Jews and well received by the multitude of his brethren. From almost being killed to second-in-command!"},{"id":19,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What festival was established to remember the Jews' deliverance?","options":["Passover","Hanukkah","Purim","Feast of Tabernacles"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 9:26-28","explanation":"The festival of Purim was established — named after 'Pur' (the lot) that Haman had cast. Jews celebrate Purim to this day, remembering how God turned their sorrow into joy and their mourning into a holiday! They celebrate on the 14th and 15th of Adar."},{"id":20,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"Over how many provinces did King Ahasuerus reign?","options":["50 provinces","100 provinces","120 provinces","127 provinces"],"correct":3,"reference":"Esther 1:1","explanation":"King Ahasuerus reigned over 127 provinces, from India to Ethiopia. This was one of the largest empires in the ancient world — and Esther was queen of it all! God placed her in an incredibly strategic position."},{"id":21,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"Who were the two eunuchs whose plot to kill the king was discovered by Mordecai?","options":["Hegai and Shaashgaz","Bigthan and Teresh","Abagtha and Zethar","Carcas and Biztha"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 2:21-23","explanation":"Bigthan (also called Bigthana) and Teresh, two of the king's eunuchs who guarded the doorway, became furious and sought to kill King Ahasuerus. But Mordecai found out and told Queen Esther, who reported it in Mordecai's name. They were both hanged, and it was written in the book of chronicles."},{"id":22,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many sons of Haman were killed?","options":["5 sons","7 sons","10 sons","12 sons"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 9:10,13-14","explanation":"Haman had ten sons, and all ten were killed by the Jews. Esther even requested that their bodies be hanged on the gallows. Their names are listed in Esther 9:7-10. Haman's entire household was brought down because of his wicked plot against God's people."},{"id":23,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Esther say was the penalty for approaching the king without being called?","options":["A fine of gold","Imprisonment for 30 days","Death, unless the king holds out the golden scepter","Banishment from the kingdom"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 4:11","explanation":"Any man or woman who went into the inner court to the king without being called had one law — to be put to death — UNLESS the king held out the golden scepter so they might live. Esther hadn't been called for thirty days. That's why she needed so much courage!"},{"id":24,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What was the name of the eunuch who was in charge of the women in the king's house?","options":["Harbona","Hegai","Hatach","Shaashgaz"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 2:8","explanation":"Hegai was the king's eunuch who was custodian of the women. He was pleased with Esther and gave her beauty preparations, her portion of food, and seven choice maidservants. He moved her and her maids to the best place in the house of the women. Even the palace workers could see something special about Esther!"},{"id":25,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What were the Jews allowed to do on the day Haman had planned for their destruction?","options":["Leave the kingdom","Gather together and protect their lives","Attack the king's enemies","Celebrate a feast only"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 8:11","explanation":"The king's new decree permitted the Jews in every city to gather together and protect their lives — to destroy, kill, and annihilate all who would assault them. Since the original decree could not be reversed (Persian law!), a new decree was made giving the Jews the right to defend themselves."},{"id":26,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Where did Naomi and her family originally come from before moving to Moab?","options":["Jerusalem","Bethlehem of Judah","Nazareth","Jericho"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:1-2","explanation":"Naomi's family was from Bethlehem of Judah (also called Bethlehem Ephrathah). They left because of a famine in the land and went to the country of Moab. Interestingly, Bethlehem means 'House of Bread' — yet there was a famine there!"},{"id":27,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Naomi's husband?","options":["Boaz","Elimelech","Mahlon","Chilion"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:2","explanation":"Naomi's husband was Elimelech, whose name means 'My God is King.' Sadly, he died in the land of Moab, leaving Naomi with her two sons, Mahlon and Chilion."},{"id":28,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What were the names of Naomi's two sons?","options":["Jacob and Esau","Mahlon and Chilion","Moses and Aaron","David and Solomon"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:2","explanation":"Naomi's sons were Mahlon and Chilion, who were Ephrathites from Bethlehem. Both of them married Moabite women — Mahlon married Ruth and Chilion married Orpah. Sadly, both sons also died in Moab."},{"id":29,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Naomi's other daughter-in-law (not Ruth)?","options":["Rachel","Orpah","Leah","Miriam"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:4","explanation":"Orpah was Naomi's other daughter-in-law. While both Orpah and Ruth initially wanted to go with Naomi back to Bethlehem, Orpah eventually kissed her mother-in-law goodbye and returned to her people and her gods. Ruth, however, clung to Naomi!"},{"id":30,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Complete Ruth's famous declaration: 'Wherever you go, I will go; wherever you lodge, ___'","options":["'I will be nearby'","'I will lodge'","'I will find my own place'","'I will wait for you'"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:16","explanation":"Ruth's beautiful words of loyalty: 'Entreat me not to leave you, or to turn back from following after you; for wherever you go, I will go; and wherever you lodge, I will lodge; your people shall be my people, and your God, my God.' This is one of the most beautiful expressions of love and loyalty in the entire Bible!"},{"id":31,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What name did Naomi say people should call her when she returned to Bethlehem?","options":["Mara","Sarah","Hagar","Deborah"],"correct":0,"reference":"Ruth 1:20","explanation":"Naomi said 'Do not call me Naomi; call me Mara, for the Almighty has dealt very bitterly with me.' Naomi means 'Pleasant' but Mara means 'Bitter.' She felt God had dealt harshly with her because she left full but came back empty."},{"id":32,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Ruth doing in Boaz's field?","options":["Planting seeds","Gleaning leftover grain","Selling bread","Watching sheep"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:2-3","explanation":"Ruth went to glean heads of grain — picking up the leftover grain that the harvesters left behind. God's law allowed the poor and foreigners to glean in the fields (Leviticus 19:9-10). Ruth 'happened' to come to Boaz's field — but we know God was guiding her steps!"},{"id":33,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did Boaz greet his reapers when he arrived at the field?","options":["'Work harder!'","'The Lord be with you!'","'How is the harvest?'","'Peace be unto you!'"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:4","explanation":"Boaz greeted his workers saying 'The Lord be with you!' and they answered 'The Lord bless you!' This tells us a lot about Boaz's character — he was a godly man who cared about his workers and acknowledged God in his daily life."},{"id":34,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What special instructions did Boaz give his workers about Ruth?","options":["Send her away","Let her glean even among the sheaves and let grain fall on purpose for her","Give her a job as a worker","Tell her to come back tomorrow"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:15-16","explanation":"Boaz told his young men: 'Let her glean even among the sheaves, and do not reproach her. Also let grain from the bundles fall purposely for her.' He went above and beyond to provide for Ruth! He also told his workers not to touch her or rebuke her."},{"id":35,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Naomi instruct Ruth to do at the threshing floor?","options":["Bring Boaz a gift of food","Wash, anoint herself, put on her best garment, and lie at his feet","Dance and celebrate the harvest","Ask Boaz for a job"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 3:3-4","explanation":"Naomi told Ruth to wash herself, anoint herself, put on her best garment, and go down to the threshing floor. After Boaz finished eating and drinking and lay down, she was to uncover his feet and lie down. This was a culturally appropriate way to ask Boaz to be her kinsman-redeemer!"},{"id":36,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Ruth ask Boaz to do at the threshing floor?","options":["Give her more grain","'Take your maidservant under your wing, for you are a close relative'","Marry Naomi","Hire her permanently"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 3:9","explanation":"Ruth said 'Take your maidservant under your wing, for you are a close relative.' She was asking Boaz to be her kinsman-redeemer — to marry her and carry on her deceased husband's family line. The phrase 'spread your wing' (or 'cover with your garment') symbolized marriage and protection."},{"id":37,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"Why couldn't Boaz immediately redeem Ruth? What had to happen first?","options":["He needed the king's permission","There was a closer relative who had the first right of redemption","He needed to finish the harvest","He had to pay off a debt first"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 3:12-13","explanation":"Boaz told Ruth that there was a kinsman-redeemer closer in relation than he was. That person had the first right to redeem. Boaz promised that if the closer relative would not redeem her, then he himself would. He had to follow God's law properly!"},{"id":38,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"How did the closer relative indicate that he was giving up his right of redemption?","options":["He signed a document","He took off his sandal and gave it to Boaz","He shook hands with Boaz","He made a public announcement"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:7-8","explanation":"In Israel, to confirm a transaction, one man took off his sandal and gave it to the other. So the close relative said to Boaz 'Buy it for yourself' and took off his sandal. This was the custom of confirmation in Israel — like signing a contract today!"},{"id":39,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Ruth and Boaz's son?","options":["Jesse","David","Obed","Solomon"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:17","explanation":"Ruth and Boaz's son was named Obed, which means 'servant' or 'worshiper.' The neighbor women named him! Here's the amazing family line: Obed was the father of Jesse, and Jesse was the father of King David — and eventually, Jesus Christ came from this very line! A Moabite woman became part of Jesus' family tree!"},{"id":40,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did the women of Bethlehem say about Ruth to Naomi?","options":["'She is a hard worker'","'She is better to you than seven sons'","'She is the most beautiful woman'","'She is very wealthy'"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:15","explanation":"The women said Ruth 'is better to you than seven sons'! In that culture, sons were highly valued, so saying Ruth was better than SEVEN sons was an incredible compliment. It showed how much Ruth's love and loyalty meant — she truly was a remarkable woman."},{"id":41,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"At which gate and with how many elders did Boaz settle the matter of redeeming Ruth?","options":["The temple gate with 7 elders","The city gate with 10 elders","The king's gate with 12 elders","The market gate with 5 elders"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:1-2","explanation":"Boaz went up to the city gate and took ten men of the elders of the city to sit down as witnesses. The city gate was where legal matters were settled in ancient Israel — it was like a courthouse. Everything was done properly and publicly!"},{"id":42,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"During which harvest season did Ruth arrive in Bethlehem with Naomi?","options":["Wheat harvest","Grape harvest","Barley harvest","Olive harvest"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 1:22","explanation":"Ruth and Naomi arrived in Bethlehem at the beginning of barley harvest. This was God's perfect timing — Ruth could immediately begin gleaning in the fields to provide food for herself and Naomi. Barley harvest was in the spring, around April."},{"id":43,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"How much barley did Ruth glean on her first day in Boaz's field?","options":["About half an ephah","About an ephah","About two ephahs","About a bushel"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:17","explanation":"Ruth gleaned about an ephah of barley — that's roughly 30-50 pounds of grain! For a single day's gleaning by one woman, this was an extraordinary amount. Naomi was amazed and asked where she had worked. Boaz's generosity, with grain being purposely dropped for her, made all the difference!"},{"id":44,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Why did the closer relative refuse to redeem Ruth?","options":["He didn't have enough money","He said it would ruin his own inheritance","He didn't like Ruth","His wife wouldn't allow it"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:6","explanation":"The closer relative said 'I cannot redeem it for myself, lest I ruin my own inheritance. You redeem my right of redemption for yourself, for I cannot redeem it.' He was worried that buying Elimelech's land and marrying Ruth would complicate his own family's inheritance. His loss was Boaz's (and Ruth's!) gain!"},{"id":45,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Hannah's husband?","options":["Eli","Elkanah","Samuel","Hophni"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:1-2","explanation":"Hannah's husband was Elkanah, from Ramathaim Zophim, of the mountains of Ephraim. He loved Hannah very much, but she was unable to have children, which caused her great sorrow."},{"id":46,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Elkanah's other wife who provoked Hannah?","options":["Peninnah","Orpah","Michal","Abigail"],"correct":0,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:2","explanation":"Peninnah was Elkanah's other wife who had children. She would provoke Hannah severely year after year, making her miserable because the Lord had closed her womb. Despite this, Hannah kept turning to God in prayer rather than fighting back!"},{"id":47,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"Where did Elkanah's family go to worship and sacrifice each year?","options":["Jerusalem","Bethlehem","Shiloh","Bethel"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:3","explanation":"The family went up to Shiloh year by year to worship and sacrifice to the Lord of hosts. Shiloh was where the tabernacle (God's dwelling place) was located at that time, before the temple was built in Jerusalem."},{"id":48,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Elkanah give Hannah at the yearly sacrifice, and why?","options":["A double portion, because he loved her","Extra money for clothing","A special robe","A gold ring"],"correct":0,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:5","explanation":"Elkanah would give Hannah a double portion (some translations say 'a worthy portion') because he loved her, even though the Lord had closed her womb. He tried to comfort her, even saying 'Am I not better to you than ten sons?' He truly cared for her!"},{"id":49,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Eli the priest think when he saw Hannah praying at the tabernacle?","options":["He thought she was singing","He thought she was drunk","He thought she was sleeping","He thought she was talking to someone"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:13-14","explanation":"Hannah was praying silently — her lips moved but her voice was not heard. Eli watched her and thought she was drunk! He said 'How long will you be drunk? Put your wine away from you!' But Hannah explained she was pouring out her soul before the Lord in deep anguish. She wasn't drunk — she was desperate for God!"},{"id":50,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What vow did Hannah make to God if He gave her a son?","options":["She would name him after Eli","She would give him to the Lord all the days of his life, and no razor would come upon his head","She would build a new tabernacle","She would bring extra offerings every year"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:11","explanation":"Hannah vowed that if God gave her a male child, she would give him to the Lord all the days of his life, and no razor would come upon his head. This was similar to a Nazirite vow (like Samson's). She was willing to give back the very thing she wanted most — what incredible faith and sacrifice!"},{"id":51,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"What did Hannah name her son?","options":["Eli","Elkanah Jr.","Samuel","Ichabod"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:20","explanation":"Hannah named her son Samuel, saying 'Because I have asked for him from the Lord.' The name Samuel sounds like the Hebrew for 'heard by God.' God heard Hannah's desperate prayer and answered her! Samuel would grow up to become one of the greatest prophets in Israel's history."},{"id":52,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"When did Hannah bring Samuel to the tabernacle to fulfill her vow?","options":["When he was born","When he was weaned","When he turned 12","When he turned 5"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:24","explanation":"Hannah waited until Samuel was weaned (probably around age 3 in that culture) before bringing him to the house of the Lord in Shiloh. She brought him along with offerings — three bulls, one ephah of flour, and a skin of wine. She kept her promise to God even though it meant giving up her beloved son!"},{"id":53,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Hannah's prayer of praise (1 Samuel 2), what does she say about the Lord?","options":["'The Lord makes poor and makes rich; He brings low and lifts up'","'The Lord helps those who help themselves'","'The Lord only blesses the wealthy'","'The Lord forgets the humble'"],"correct":0,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:7","explanation":"Hannah's beautiful prayer declares 'The Lord makes poor and makes rich; He brings low and lifts up.' Her prayer is full of praise about God's power, sovereignty, and care for the humble. Hannah understood that God reverses situations — He lifts up the lowly and brings down the proud!"},{"id":54,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Hannah's song, she says 'The barren has borne ___' — how many?","options":["Five","Seven","Three","Ten"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:5","explanation":"Hannah declared 'The barren has borne seven, and she who has many children has become feeble.' Seven represents completeness and perfection in the Bible. God completely reversed Hannah's situation — and indeed, after Samuel, Hannah had three more sons and two daughters (1 Samuel 2:21)!"},{"id":55,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Hannah bring to Samuel every year when she visited him at the tabernacle?","options":["A new pair of sandals","A little robe","A basket of bread","A new blanket"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:19","explanation":"Each year, Hannah made a little robe and brought it to Samuel when she came up with her husband to offer the yearly sacrifice. Can you imagine her lovingly sewing that robe, making it a little bigger each year as her boy grew? A mother's love never stops!"},{"id":56,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many more children did Hannah have after Samuel?","options":["Two sons and one daughter","Three sons and two daughters","One son and one daughter","Four sons"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:21","explanation":"God blessed Hannah with three more sons and two daughters! She gave up one child to God's service, and He blessed her with five more. God always honors those who honor Him with their sacrifices. Meanwhile, Samuel grew before the Lord and became a mighty prophet."},{"id":57,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"Hannah's prayer in 1 Samuel 2:1 begins with which words?","options":["'My soul magnifies the Lord'","'My heart rejoices in the Lord'","'Praise the Lord, O my soul'","'I will bless the Lord at all times'"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:1","explanation":"Hannah's prayer begins: 'My heart rejoices in the Lord; my horn is exalted in the Lord.' The 'horn' symbolizes strength and power. Hannah went from weeping and not eating to singing praises with a full heart! Her prayer is considered one of the greatest prayers in the Old Testament and even echoes in Mary's Magnificat centuries later."},{"id":58,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What blessing did Eli give to Elkanah and Hannah after she dedicated Samuel?","options":["He gave them gold","He prayed that God would give them more children","He gave them land","He invited them to live in Shiloh"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:20","explanation":"Eli blessed Elkanah and his wife, saying 'The Lord give you descendants from this woman for the loan that was lent to the Lord.' Hannah had 'lent' Samuel to God, and God honored that sacrifice through Eli's blessing. And indeed, God answered — Hannah had five more children!"},{"id":59,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Abigail's first husband?","options":["David","Nabal","Saul","Jesse"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:3","explanation":"Abigail's first husband was Nabal, a very rich man from Maon who had property in Carmel. He had 3,000 sheep and 1,000 goats. The Bible describes him as harsh and evil in his doings — quite the opposite of his wise and beautiful wife!"},{"id":60,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What does the name 'Nabal' mean?","options":["Wealthy","Fool","Strong","Noble"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:25","explanation":"Abigail herself said: 'For as his name is, so is he: Nabal is his name, and folly is with him!' The name Nabal literally means 'Fool.' He certainly lived up to his name by insulting David and refusing to show kindness!"},{"id":61,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"How is Abigail described in the Bible?","options":["Tall and strong","A woman of good understanding and beautiful appearance","Quiet and shy","Wealthy and powerful"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:3","explanation":"The Bible says Abigail was 'a woman of good understanding and beautiful appearance.' She had both inner wisdom and outer beauty — brains AND beauty! This combination of understanding and grace is exactly what saved the day when Nabal's foolishness put everyone in danger."},{"id":62,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"Why did David send messengers to Nabal?","options":["To declare war","To ask for food and provisions because David's men had protected Nabal's shepherds","To buy his sheep","To invite him to a feast"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:7-8","explanation":"David's men had been like a protective wall around Nabal's shepherds in the wilderness — they didn't take anything and kept them safe from harm. During sheep-shearing time (a time of feasting and generosity), David politely asked Nabal for whatever provisions he could spare. It was a reasonable request!"},{"id":63,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did Nabal respond to David's messengers?","options":["He gave them food generously","He insulted David and refused to give anything","He invited them to stay","He was too afraid to respond"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:10-11","explanation":"Nabal insulted David, saying 'Who is David, and who is the son of Jesse? There are many servants nowadays who break away each one from his master.' He refused to give any bread, water, or meat to David's men. He basically called David a runaway slave! Not smart when David had 600 armed men!"},{"id":64,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did David plan to do after Nabal's insult?","options":["Write an angry letter","Report Nabal to King Saul","Take 400 men and destroy Nabal and all his males","Steal Nabal's sheep"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:13,22","explanation":"David was furious! He told his men 'Every man gird on his sword' and took 400 armed men to attack Nabal. He swore an oath: 'May God do so, and more also, to the enemies of David, if I leave one male of all who belong to him by morning light.' David was about to commit mass slaughter because of one fool's insult!"},{"id":65,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"Who told Abigail about Nabal's foolish response to David?","options":["Nabal himself","One of the young men (servants)","David's messengers","A neighbor"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:14","explanation":"One of the young men (servants) told Abigail everything — how David's men had been good to them, how Nabal had railed against David's messengers, and how evil was determined against their master. The servant knew Nabal so well that he said 'he is such a scoundrel that one cannot speak to him.' Even the servants knew Nabal was foolish!"},{"id":66,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"What provisions did Abigail quickly gather to bring to David?","options":["200 loaves of bread, 2 skins of wine, 5 sheep, 5 seahs of roasted grain, 100 clusters of raisins, and 200 cakes of figs","100 loaves and 50 sheep","10 donkeys loaded with gold","500 loaves and 10 skins of wine"],"correct":0,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:18","explanation":"Abigail acted FAST! She gathered 200 loaves of bread, 2 skins of wine, 5 sheep already dressed, 5 seahs of roasted grain, 100 clusters of raisins, and 200 cakes of figs. She loaded them on donkeys and rode out to meet David. She was smart, quick, and generous — the opposite of her husband!"},{"id":67,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Abigail do when she saw David?","options":["She ran away in fear","She fell on her face before David and bowed to the ground","She demanded he leave","She offered him money"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:23","explanation":"When Abigail saw David, she quickly dismounted from her donkey, fell on her face before David, and bowed down to the ground. She showed great humility and respect. Then she gave one of the wisest speeches in the Bible, taking the blame upon herself and urging David not to shed blood."},{"id":68,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"What key argument did Abigail use to convince David not to attack?","options":["She threatened to report him to King Saul","She said shedding blood would be a burden on his conscience when God made him ruler over Israel","She said Nabal would apologize","She offered David all of Nabal's property"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:30-31","explanation":"Abigail wisely said that when the Lord made David ruler over Israel, he would not want this act of bloodshed on his conscience — 'that you have shed blood without cause or that my lord has avenged himself.' She saw David's future as king even before he did! Her wisdom saved David from a terrible sin."},{"id":69,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did David respond to Abigail's wise words?","options":["He ignored her","He blessed God for sending her and said she had kept him from bloodshed","He was angry at her","He told her to go home"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:32-34","explanation":"David said 'Blessed is the Lord God of Israel, who sent you this day to meet me! And blessed is your advice and blessed are you, because you have kept me this day from coming to bloodshed and from avenging myself with my own hand.' David recognized that God had sent Abigail to stop him from sinning!"},{"id":70,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Nabal doing when Abigail returned home from meeting David?","options":["Working in the fields","Sleeping","Holding a feast like a king's feast, and was very drunk","Praying at the temple"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:36","explanation":"While his wife had just saved his entire household from destruction, Nabal was holding a feast in his house 'like the feast of a king,' and 'his heart was merry within him, for he was very drunk.' He had no idea how close he had come to death! Abigail wisely waited until morning to tell him."},{"id":71,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What happened to Nabal when Abigail told him everything the next morning?","options":["He apologized to David","His heart died within him and he became like a stone","He fled the country","He praised Abigail for her wisdom"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:37-38","explanation":"When Nabal sobered up and Abigail told him everything, 'his heart died within him, and he became like a stone.' About ten days later, the Lord struck Nabal and he died. It appears he may have had a stroke or heart attack from the shock. God judged Nabal for his wickedness."},{"id":72,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who did Abigail marry after Nabal died?","options":["King Saul","Boaz","David","Jonathan"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:39-42","explanation":"When David heard that Nabal had died, he sent a proposal to Abigail, and she became his wife. She humbly said she would be a servant to wash the feet of David's servants. Her wisdom, beauty, and godly character won David's heart. From being married to a fool, God promoted her to become the wife of the future king!"},{"id":73,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many servants went with Abigail when she went to become David's wife?","options":["Three","Five","Ten","Twelve"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:42","explanation":"Abigail rose in haste and rode on a donkey, with five of her maidens attending her, and she followed the messengers of David and became his wife. She didn't hesitate — she acted quickly and decisively, just as she had when she prevented David from attacking Nabal."},{"id":74,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Abigail call herself when speaking to David?","options":["A queen","Your maidservant","A prophetess","A noble woman"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:24-25","explanation":"Abigail repeatedly referred to herself as David's 'maidservant' — showing deep humility. Despite being wealthy and wise, she humbled herself completely. She said 'On me, my lord, on me let this iniquity be!' She took the blame for Nabal's foolishness upon herself. What a picture of humility and wisdom!"},{"id":75,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Deborah held two important roles in Israel. What were they?","options":["Queen and priestess","Prophetess and judge","Teacher and healer","Warrior and singer"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:4","explanation":"Deborah was both a prophetess and a judge of Israel — she was the only woman to serve as a judge! The children of Israel came up to her for judgment. She sat under the palm tree of Deborah between Ramah and Bethel in the mountains of Ephraim. She was a true leader appointed by God!"},{"id":76,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"Who was the king of Canaan who oppressed Israel for 20 years during Deborah's time?","options":["Sisera","Jabin","Barak","Heber"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:2-3","explanation":"Jabin, king of Canaan, who reigned in Hazor, oppressed the children of Israel harshly for twenty years. His military commander was Sisera, who had 900 chariots of iron — a terrifying military force! But God was about to turn things around through Deborah."},{"id":77,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"How many iron chariots did Sisera, the commander of Jabin's army, have?","options":["100","300","500","900"],"correct":3,"reference":"Judges 4:3","explanation":"Sisera had NINE HUNDRED chariots of iron! In ancient warfare, iron chariots were like tanks — they were the most advanced military technology of the time. Israel had none. But God doesn't need military equipment to win battles — He uses willing hearts!"},{"id":78,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who did Deborah summon to lead Israel's army into battle?","options":["Joshua","Gideon","Barak","Samson"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:6","explanation":"Deborah summoned Barak the son of Abinoam from Kedesh in Naphtali. She told him that God commanded him to take 10,000 men from Naphtali and Zebulun and go to Mount Tabor. God would deliver Sisera into his hand!"},{"id":79,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What condition did Barak set before agreeing to go into battle?","options":["He wanted more soldiers","He wanted better weapons","He said he would only go if Deborah went with him","He wanted a sign from God"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:8","explanation":"Barak said to Deborah: 'If you will go with me, then I will go; but if you will not go with me, I will not go!' He wanted Deborah — God's prophetess — with him on the battlefield. Deborah agreed to go but warned him that the glory of the victory would go to a woman, not to him."},{"id":80,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"How many men did Barak gather from Naphtali and Zebulun?","options":["1,000","5,000","10,000","30,000"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:10","explanation":"Barak called Zebulun and Naphtali to Kedesh and gathered 10,000 men. With Deborah at his side, they went up to Mount Tabor. 10,000 foot soldiers against 900 iron chariots — humanly speaking, it was impossible. But with God, all things are possible!"},{"id":81,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who killed Sisera, the enemy commander?","options":["Barak","Deborah","Jael","An Israelite soldier"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:21","explanation":"Jael, the wife of Heber the Kenite, killed Sisera. When Sisera fled the battle on foot and came to Jael's tent, she invited him in, covered him, gave him milk to drink, and when he fell asleep, she drove a tent peg through his temple. She was the woman Deborah prophesied would receive the glory!"},{"id":82,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Jael use to kill Sisera?","options":["A sword","A tent peg and a hammer","A spear","An arrow"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:21","explanation":"Jael took a tent peg and a hammer, and went softly to Sisera while he was fast asleep and exhausted. She drove the tent peg through his temple and into the ground. As a nomadic woman, she would have been very skilled at driving tent pegs — she used the tools she had available to accomplish God's purpose!"},{"id":83,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Jael give Sisera to drink when he asked for water?","options":["Water","Wine","Milk","Juice"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:19","explanation":"When Sisera asked for water, Jael opened a jug of milk and gave him a drink, then covered him. Warm milk would have made the already exhausted Sisera even sleepier — some think she gave him curdled milk (yogurt), which would have been even more sleep-inducing!"},{"id":84,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Deborah's song (Judges 5), what does she say fought against Sisera from heaven?","options":["Angels","The stars","Thunder and lightning","Fire"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:20","explanation":"'They fought from the heavens; the stars from their courses fought against Sisera.' This poetic language in Deborah's victory song describes how all of creation — even the stars — fought on Israel's side. God used everything at His disposal to defeat the enemy!"},{"id":85,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Deborah's song, what river swept away the enemy?","options":["The Jordan River","The Kishon River","The Nile River","The Euphrates River"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:21","explanation":"'The torrent of Kishon swept them away, that ancient torrent, the torrent of Kishon.' God sent a rainstorm that caused the Kishon River to flood, turning the battlefield into mud. The 900 iron chariots that were Sisera's greatest advantage became useless in the mud — they actually became a trap! God turned the enemy's strength into their weakness."},{"id":86,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What title does Deborah give herself in her song of victory?","options":["A warrior in Israel","A queen in Israel","A mother in Israel","A priestess in Israel"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 5:7","explanation":"Deborah calls herself 'a mother in Israel.' She said village life had ceased until she arose as a mother in Israel. This beautiful title shows that Deborah saw her leadership role as nurturing and protecting God's people — like a mother cares for her children. True leadership is about serving others!"},{"id":87,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"How long did the land have rest after Deborah and Barak's victory?","options":["20 years","40 years","60 years","80 years"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:31","explanation":"After this great victory, the land had rest for forty years! That's an entire generation of peace because Deborah was obedient to God's calling and Barak was willing to fight. One act of faith and courage brought decades of peace to the entire nation."},{"id":88,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"Where did Deborah sit when she judged Israel?","options":["In the tabernacle at Shiloh","Under the palm tree of Deborah between Ramah and Bethel","At the city gate of Jerusalem","By the Jordan River"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:5","explanation":"Deborah sat under the palm tree of Deborah between Ramah and Bethel in the mountains of Ephraim, and the children of Israel came up to her for judgment. The palm tree became her 'courtroom' — a place where people could find wisdom, justice, and godly counsel. The tree was even named after her!"},{"id":89,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"Who was Deborah's husband?","options":["Barak","Lappidoth","Heber","Jabin"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:4","explanation":"Deborah was the wife of Lappidoth. His name means 'torches' or 'flames.' While the Bible doesn't tell us much about Lappidoth, he was married to one of the most remarkable women in the entire Bible — a prophetess, judge, poet, and military strategist!"},{"id":90,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Deborah's song, what is the last line of the song?","options":["'Let all the earth praise the Lord'","'Let all Your enemies perish, O Lord! But let those who love Him be like the sun when it comes out in full strength'","'Blessed be the Lord forever'","'The Lord reigns forever and ever'"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:31","explanation":"The song ends with: 'Thus let all Your enemies perish, O Lord! But let those who love Him be like the sun when it comes out in full strength.' What a powerful image — those who love God shine like the sun at its brightest! This was followed by forty years of peace."},{"id":91,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of Elizabeth's husband?","options":["Joseph","Zacharias","Simeon","Herod"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:5","explanation":"Elizabeth's husband was Zacharias (also spelled Zechariah), a priest of the division of Abijah. Both Zacharias and Elizabeth were righteous before God, walking in all the commandments and ordinances of the Lord blamelessly. They were a godly couple!"},{"id":92,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"From which priestly family was Elizabeth descended?","options":["The daughters of Aaron","The daughters of Moses","The daughters of Levi","The daughters of David"],"correct":0,"reference":"Luke 1:5","explanation":"Elizabeth was from the daughters of Aaron — meaning she was from a priestly family on both sides! Her husband Zacharias was a priest, and she herself was descended from Aaron, the first high priest of Israel. Their son John the Baptist had priestly blood but became a prophet."},{"id":93,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Zacharias doing when the angel appeared to him?","options":["Praying at home","Burning incense in the temple","Reading the scrolls","Teaching the people"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:8-11","explanation":"Zacharias was serving as priest before God, and it was his turn to burn incense in the temple of the Lord. The whole multitude of people was praying outside. An angel of the Lord appeared, standing on the right side of the altar of incense. Burning incense was a once-in-a-lifetime honor for most priests!"},{"id":94,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of the angel who appeared to both Zacharias and Mary?","options":["Michael","Gabriel","Raphael","Uriel"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:19,26","explanation":"The angel Gabriel appeared to both Zacharias in the temple and to Mary in Nazareth. Gabriel told Zacharias: 'I am Gabriel, who stands in the presence of God, and was sent to speak to you and bring you these glad tidings.' Gabriel is one of only two angels named in the Bible (the other is Michael)."},{"id":95,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Why was Zacharias struck mute (unable to speak)?","options":["He was sick","He did not believe the angel's message about having a son","He spoke disrespectfully to the angel","It was a sign of blessing"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:18-20","explanation":"Zacharias doubted the angel's message, saying 'How shall I know this? For I am an old man, and my wife is well advanced in years.' Because he did not believe Gabriel's words, he was struck mute and could not speak until the day the prophecy was fulfilled. Sometimes doubt has consequences!"},{"id":96,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What did the angel tell Mary she would name her son?","options":["John","Emmanuel","Jesus","David"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:31","explanation":"The angel said: 'And behold, you will conceive in your womb and bring forth a Son, and shall call His name JESUS.' The name Jesus (Yeshua in Hebrew) means 'the Lord saves' or 'Savior.' He would be called the Son of the Highest and would reign on the throne of David forever!"},{"id":97,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Elizabeth's baby do when Mary greeted Elizabeth?","options":["The baby was still","The baby leaped in Elizabeth's womb","The baby kicked gently","Nothing happened"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:41","explanation":"When Elizabeth heard Mary's greeting, the baby (John) leaped in her womb, and Elizabeth was filled with the Holy Spirit! Even before birth, baby John recognized the presence of Jesus (still in Mary's womb). Elizabeth exclaimed with a loud voice: 'Blessed are you among women, and blessed is the fruit of your womb!'"},{"id":98,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Elizabeth call Mary when she greeted her?","options":["My sister","My friend","The mother of my Lord","The chosen one"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:43","explanation":"Elizabeth, filled with the Holy Spirit, said: 'But why is this granted to me, that the mother of my Lord should come to me?' Elizabeth recognized — by the Holy Spirit — that Mary was carrying the Messiah, the Lord! She was humble enough to honor her younger relative."},{"id":99,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Mary's song of praise is known as the Magnificat. What are its opening words?","options":["'Praise the Lord, O my soul'","'My soul magnifies the Lord'","'Blessed be the God of Israel'","'The Lord is my shepherd'"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:46-47","explanation":"Mary's beautiful song begins: 'My soul magnifies the Lord, and my spirit has rejoiced in God my Savior.' The word 'Magnificat' comes from the Latin translation of 'magnifies.' Mary's song echoes Hannah's prayer from 1 Samuel 2 — both women praised God for His mercy to the humble and His power over the proud!"},{"id":100,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"How long did Mary stay with Elizabeth?","options":["One week","One month","About three months","Six months"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:56","explanation":"Mary stayed with Elizabeth about three months and then returned to her house. Since Elizabeth was six months pregnant when Mary arrived, Mary likely stayed until around the time of John's birth. What a special time of fellowship and encouragement between these two women chosen by God!"},{"id":101,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did the neighbors and relatives want to name Elizabeth's baby?","options":["Zacharias, after his father","Aaron, after Elizabeth's ancestor","Gabriel, after the angel","Eli, after the priest"],"correct":0,"reference":"Luke 1:59","explanation":"On the eighth day, when they came to circumcise the child, the neighbors and relatives wanted to name him Zacharias after his father. This was a common custom. But Elizabeth firmly said 'No; he shall be called John!' They were all surprised because nobody in the family had that name."},{"id":102,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did Zacharias confirm the baby's name?","options":["He shouted it out loud","He asked for a writing tablet and wrote 'His name is John'","He nodded his head","He pointed to Elizabeth"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:63","explanation":"Since Zacharias was still mute, he asked for a writing tablet and wrote 'His name is John.' And immediately his mouth was opened and his tongue loosed, and he spoke, praising God! The moment he obeyed God's instruction about the name, his speech was restored. Everyone who heard about it was amazed!"},{"id":103,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Mary's Magnificat, she says God has 'put down the mighty from their ___'","options":["Kingdoms","Thrones","Horses","Towers"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:52","explanation":"Mary sang: 'He has put down the mighty from their thrones, and exalted the lowly.' Mary's song is revolutionary — God reverses the world's values! The proud are scattered, the mighty are brought down, the rich are sent away empty, but the humble and hungry are lifted up and filled. This is the heart of God's kingdom!"},{"id":104,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Luke 1, how many months pregnant was Elizabeth when Gabriel visited Mary?","options":["Three months","Five months","Six months","Eight months"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:26,36","explanation":"Gabriel told Mary: 'Now indeed, Elizabeth your relative has also conceived a son in her old age; and this is now the sixth month for her who was called barren.' Elizabeth was six months pregnant when Mary received her own amazing news. Gabriel used Elizabeth's miracle pregnancy as encouragement for Mary to believe!"},{"id":105,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"In John 19:25-27, who was standing by the cross of Jesus?","options":["Only the disciples","His mother Mary, His mother's sister, Mary the wife of Clopas, and Mary Magdalene","Only Mary Magdalene","Peter and John only"],"correct":1,"reference":"John 19:25","explanation":"Standing by the cross were His mother Mary, His mother's sister, Mary the wife of Clopas, and Mary Magdalene. Even in His darkest hour, faithful women stood by Jesus. Mary, who had been told a sword would pierce her soul (Luke 2:35), watched her son suffer on the cross."},{"id":106,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"At the cross, who did Jesus entrust His mother Mary to?","options":["Peter","James","The disciple whom He loved (John)","His brother Jude"],"correct":2,"reference":"John 19:26-27","explanation":"Jesus saw His mother and the disciple whom He loved (believed to be John) standing by, and said to Mary 'Woman, behold your son!' and to the disciple 'Behold your mother!' From that hour, that disciple took her to his own home. Even while dying on the cross, Jesus cared for His mother. What love!"},{"id":107,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"What was Mary's response when the angel told her she would conceive a son?","options":["She was afraid and ran away","'How can this be, since I do not know a man?'","She immediately said yes","She asked for a sign"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:34","explanation":"Mary asked 'How can this be, since I do not know a man?' Unlike Zacharias who doubted, Mary asked HOW — she believed it was possible, she just wanted to understand the mechanism. The angel explained that the Holy Spirit would come upon her and the power of the Highest would overshadow her. Then Mary humbly said 'Let it be to me according to your word.'"},{"id":108,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"Elizabeth hid herself for how many months after she conceived?","options":["One month","Three months","Five months","Seven months"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:24","explanation":"After Elizabeth conceived, she hid herself five months, saying 'Thus the Lord has dealt with me, in the days when He looked on me, to take away my reproach among people.' In that culture, being barren was considered a reproach. Elizabeth spent those months in gratitude and wonder at God's amazing grace!"},{"id":109,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Elizabeth say was 'blessed' about Mary?","options":["Her beauty","Her wealth","She who believed, for there will be a fulfillment","Her family lineage"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:45","explanation":"Elizabeth said: 'Blessed is she who believed, for there will be a fulfillment of those things which were told her from the Lord.' Elizabeth commended Mary's FAITH — her willingness to believe God's incredible promise. Faith is what made Mary blessed, not just the honor she received!"},{"id":110,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Mary's Magnificat, she says 'He has filled the hungry with good things, and the rich He has sent away ___'","options":["Weeping","Empty","Ashamed","Punished"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:53","explanation":"Mary proclaimed: 'He has filled the hungry with good things, and the rich He has sent away empty.' This powerful verse shows God's heart for those in need. Those who recognize their need for God are filled; those who think they have everything are left with nothing. It's about spiritual hunger, not just physical!"},{"id":111,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What was the name of the seven-day feast the king gave after the 180-day display?","options":["A feast for the people in Shushan the citadel","The Feast of Purim","The King's Anniversary","The Royal Banquet"],"correct":0,"reference":"Esther 1:5","explanation":"After the 180-day display, the king gave a feast lasting seven days for all the people in Shushan the citadel, from great to small, in the court of the garden of the king's palace. Meanwhile, Queen Vashti also made a feast for the women in the royal palace."},{"id":112,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"What family line connects Ruth to Jesus Christ?","options":["Ruth - Obed - Jesse - David","Ruth - Jesse - David - Solomon","Ruth - Boaz - David - Solomon","Ruth - Obed - Saul - David"],"correct":0,"reference":"Ruth 4:17,22; Matthew 1:5-6","explanation":"The genealogy goes: Ruth and Boaz had Obed, Obed had Jesse, and Jesse had David the king! And from David's line came Jesus Christ. A Moabite woman, who chose to follow the God of Israel, became the great-grandmother of King David and an ancestor of Jesus. God truly uses anyone who is willing!"},{"id":113,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Hannah's prayer, she mentions what about the pillars of the earth?","options":["God shakes them","The pillars of the earth are the Lord's, and He has set the world upon them","They will crumble","They reach to heaven"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:8","explanation":"Hannah declared: 'For the pillars of the earth are the Lord's, and He has set the world upon them.' She praised God as the Creator and Sustainer of everything. He raises the poor from the dust and lifts the beggar from the ash heap to set them among princes. Hannah understood that GOD controls everything!"},{"id":114,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"Who was Heber the Kenite, and why is he mentioned in the story of Deborah?","options":["He was an Israelite spy","He was a Kenite who had separated from his people; his wife Jael killed Sisera","He was Deborah's advisor","He was Barak's armor bearer"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:11,17","explanation":"Heber the Kenite had separated from the other Kenites (descendants of Moses' father-in-law) and pitched his tent near Kedesh. There was peace between Heber's family and King Jabin, which is why Sisera fled to Jael's tent thinking he was safe. But Jael chose God's side over political alliances!"},{"id":115,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Mary say about herself in her song of praise?","options":["She was the greatest woman alive","'He has regarded the lowly state of His maidservant'","She deserved this honor","She was the most righteous woman"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:48","explanation":"Mary humbly said: 'For He has regarded the lowly state of His maidservant; for behold, henceforth all generations will call me blessed.' Despite being chosen for the greatest honor any woman could receive, Mary remained humble and gave all glory to God. She saw herself as God's servant, not as someone special in herself."},{"id":116,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What are the names of the seven eunuchs King Ahasuerus sent to bring Queen Vashti before him?","options":["Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcas","Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Abagtha, Zethar, and Hegai","Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Hatach, Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcas","Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Teresh, Zethar, and Carcas"],"correct":0,"reference":"Esther 1:10","explanation":"That's a lot of names to remember! King Ahasuerus sent seven eunuchs to bring Vashti to his banquet. Try saying all seven names fast -- Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcas!"},{"id":117,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"Which prince of Persia and Media advised King Ahasuerus about what to do with Queen Vashti?","options":["Admatha","Memucan","Carshena","Marsena"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 1:16-21","explanation":"Memucan spoke up and told the king that Vashti's refusal wasn't just a problem for the king -- it was a problem for every husband in the kingdom! He suggested the king make a royal decree about it."},{"id":118,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was the royal decree that Memucan suggested after Vashti's refusal?","options":["That Vashti should be put in prison","That Vashti shall come no more before King Ahasuerus and her royal position be given to another","That all women must attend the king's feasts","That Vashti should be banished from the kingdom entirely"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 1:19","explanation":"Memucan's advice was that Vashti would never come before the king again and her royal position would go to someone better. This is how God was setting the stage for Esther to become queen!"},{"id":119,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"According to Memucan, what would the royal decree cause all wives to do?","options":["Fear their husbands","Honor their husbands, both great and small","Obey every command without question","Attend all royal banquets"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 1:20","explanation":"Memucan said that when the decree went out across the huge empire, all wives would honor their husbands, whether rich or poor, great or small. That's a pretty big rule for one person's refusal!"},{"id":120,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"During the twelve months of beauty preparation, how many months were specifically with oil of myrrh?","options":["Three months","Six months","Nine months","Twelve months"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 2:12","explanation":"Six whole months just with oil of myrrh! That's half a year of one beauty treatment. Then they had six more months with perfumes and other preparations. These girls got the ultimate spa experience!"},{"id":121,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who told Esther not to reveal her Jewish nationality or family background?","options":["Hegai","Hatach","Mordecai","Elkanah"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 2:10","explanation":"Mordecai, Esther's wise cousin who raised her, told her to keep her Jewish identity a secret. This was part of God's amazing plan to protect His people later on!"},{"id":122,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"When King Ahasuerus gave Haman authority over the Jewish people, what did he give Haman as a sign of that authority?","options":["His crown","His sword","His signet ring","His royal robe"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 3:10","explanation":"The king took his signet ring off his own hand and gave it to Haman! A signet ring was like a royal stamp -- whatever Haman sealed with it had the power of the king behind it. That's a LOT of power for a bad guy!"},{"id":123,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"After Haman was hanged, who received the king's signet ring?","options":["Esther","Hatach","Harbona","Mordecai"],"correct":3,"reference":"Esther 8:2","explanation":"The king took his signet ring that he had taken back from Haman and gave it to Mordecai! What an amazing reversal -- the ring went from the enemy of the Jews to the hero of the Jews!"},{"id":124,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was the name of the eunuch Esther sent to Mordecai to find out why he was in mourning?","options":["Hegai","Harbona","Hatach","Haman"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 4:5","explanation":"Hatach was the king's eunuch appointed to attend Esther. He became the messenger between Esther and Mordecai, carrying important messages back and forth through the palace!"},{"id":125,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"What famous words did Esther say before she decided to go before the king uninvited?","options":["\"The Lord is my strength and my shield\"","\"If I perish, I perish!\"","\"God will save His people\"","\"I will trust in the Lord forever\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 4:16","explanation":"\"If I perish, I perish!\" -- what incredible bravery! Esther knew she could die for going to the king without being called, but she was willing to risk her life for her people. That takes real courage!"},{"id":126,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"When Esther approached King Ahasuerus uninvited and he held out the golden scepter, what did Esther do?","options":["She bowed to the ground","She touched the top of the scepter","She kissed the king's hand","She knelt before the throne"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 5:2","explanation":"Esther went near and touched the top of the golden scepter! This was the sign that the king accepted her and she would not be put to death. What a relief that must have been!"},{"id":127,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"What did King Ahasuerus offer Esther when she came before him, up to how much?","options":["Up to a third of the kingdom","Up to half the kingdom","Up to all the kingdom","Up to a quarter of the kingdom"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 5:3","explanation":"The king said he would give Esther up to half the kingdom! That shows how much the king loved Esther. But Esther didn't ask for riches -- she asked the king and Haman to come to a banquet. Smart move!"},{"id":128,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Haman's wife Zeresh and his friends originally advise him to build for Mordecai?","options":["A prison cell","A gallows fifty cubits high","A pit in the ground","A stake in the public square"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 5:14","explanation":"Zeresh and Haman's friends told him to make a gallows fifty cubits high (about 75 feet!) and ask the king to hang Mordecai on it. They thought it was a great plan, but God had other ideas!"},{"id":129,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"After Haman was forced to honor Mordecai, what did his wife Zeresh and his wise men tell him?","options":["\"Fight harder against Mordecai\"","\"If Mordecai is of Jewish descent, you will not prevail against him but will surely fall before him\"","\"Flee the kingdom immediately\"","\"Beg the king for mercy\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 6:13","explanation":"Even Haman's own wife and friends could see the writing on the wall! They warned him that if Mordecai was Jewish, Haman would surely fall. They were absolutely right -- God protects His people!"},{"id":130,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"Which eunuch suggested to the king that the gallows Haman built for Mordecai could be used for Haman himself?","options":["Hatach","Hegai","Harbona","Bigtha"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 7:9","explanation":"Harbona, one of the eunuchs serving the king, spoke up and pointed out the fifty-cubit gallows Haman had built for Mordecai. The king immediately said, 'Hang him on it!' Talk about perfect timing!"},{"id":131,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"In Esther chapter 8, how did Esther approach the king to plead for her people against Haman's decree?","options":["She sent a letter through Hatach","She fell down at his feet and wept, imploring him","She stood boldly at the throne","She sent Mordecai to speak for her"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 8:3","explanation":"Esther fell down at the king's feet, weeping and begging him to stop Haman's evil plan against her people. She was so passionate about saving the Jews that she humbled herself completely before the king!"},{"id":132,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did the second decree, issued in Mordecai's name, allow the Jews to do?","options":["Leave the kingdom peacefully","Gather together, protect their lives, destroy, kill, and plunder those who would assault them","Take Haman's property and divide it equally","Move to a separate province for safety"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 8:11","explanation":"The new decree gave the Jews the right to gather together and defend themselves! They could fight back against anyone who tried to attack them. God turned a death sentence into a victory plan!"},{"id":133,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"On what exact date were the Jews supposed to be destroyed according to Haman's decree, and on what date did they instead defend themselves?","options":["The 12th day of the month of Adar","The 13th day of the month of Adar","The 14th day of the month of Adar","The 15th day of the month of Adar"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 3:13; 8:12; 9:1","explanation":"The 13th day of Adar was supposed to be doomsday for the Jews, but God flipped it completely! Instead of being destroyed, the Jews defeated their enemies on that very same day. What an amazing turnaround!"},{"id":134,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"After the Jews' victory, the days of Purim were established as days of what?","options":["Mourning and prayer","Feasting and joy, sending presents to one another and gifts to the poor","Fasting and repentance","Building temples and monuments"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 9:22","explanation":"Purim became an awesome celebration! The Jews feasted, had joy, sent presents to each other, and gave gifts to the poor. It's like a combination of a party and a charity event -- how cool is that!"},{"id":135,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"When Mordecai went out from the king's presence in royal apparel, what colors and materials were his garments?","options":["Purple and scarlet with a crown of silver","Blue and white with a great crown of gold and a garment of fine linen and purple","Red and gold with a crown of jewels","White and gold with a turban of fine linen"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 8:15","explanation":"Mordecai looked amazing! He wore blue and white with a great crown of gold and a garment of fine linen and purple. He went from wearing sackcloth and ashes to royal robes -- what a glow-up!"},{"id":136,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many men did the Jews kill in the citadel of Shushan (the capital) on the 13th of Adar?","options":["200 men","300 men","500 men","800 men"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 9:6","explanation":"The Jews killed 500 men in the citadel of Shushan alone! And that doesn't even count Haman's ten sons. God gave His people a mighty victory right in the heart of the enemy's territory!"},{"id":137,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"Before the Jews' battle on the 13th of Adar, what had many people in the provinces done because the fear of the Jews fell on them?","options":["They fled the country","They became Jews themselves","They built walls around their cities","They hid in the mountains"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 8:17","explanation":"Many people of the land actually became Jews because the fear of the Jews fell upon them! When God is on your side, even your enemies can see His power and want to be part of His people!"},{"id":138,"category":"esther","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Esther's second petition to the king regarding Haman's ten sons after they were killed?","options":["That their property be given to the Jews","That their bodies be hanged on the gallows","That their families be banished","That a monument be built over their graves"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 9:13","explanation":"Esther asked that Haman's ten sons, who had already been killed, be hanged on the gallows for everyone to see. This was a public display showing that the enemies of God's people were completely defeated!"},{"id":139,"category":"esther","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many additional men were killed in Shushan on the 14th day of Adar after Esther's second petition?","options":["100 men","200 men","300 men","500 men"],"correct":2,"reference":"Esther 9:15","explanation":"The Jews in Shushan killed 300 more men on the 14th of Adar. That's 500 on the first day plus 300 on the second -- 800 total in Shushan alone! The enemies of God's people were completely wiped out!"},{"id":140,"category":"esther","difficulty":"easy","question":"According to Esther 9:22, what were the Jews instructed to send to the poor during Purim?","options":["Prayers","Gifts","Letters","Clothing"],"correct":1,"reference":"Esther 9:22","explanation":"Part of celebrating Purim was sending gifts to the poor! God wanted His people to remember that victory isn't just about celebrating -- it's also about taking care of those who need help. How awesome is that!"},{"id":141,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Why did Elimelech and his family leave Bethlehem and go to the country of Moab?","options":["Because of a war","Because of a famine in the land","Because the king commanded them to leave","Because they wanted to trade goods"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 1:1","explanation":"There was a famine in Bethlehem, which means there wasn't enough food. So Elimelech took his family to Moab looking for food. Interesting fact: Bethlehem means 'house of bread' but it had no bread!"},{"id":142,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How long did Naomi's family live in the country of Moab?","options":["About 5 years","About 7 years","About 10 years","About 15 years"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 1:4","explanation":"Naomi's family lived in Moab for about 10 years! During that time, her sons married Moabite women, Ruth and Orpah. But sadly, Naomi's husband and both sons died during those years."},{"id":143,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What news did Naomi hear that made her decide to return to Bethlehem from Moab?","options":["That a new king had risen in Judah","That her relatives had built her a home","That the Lord had visited His people by giving them bread","That the temple had been rebuilt"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 1:6","explanation":"Naomi heard that the Lord had visited His people by giving them bread! The famine was over and God had blessed the land again. This good news was what started the journey that would change Ruth's life forever!"},{"id":144,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What nationality was Ruth?","options":["An Israelite","An Egyptian","A Moabitess","A Philistine"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 1:22; 2:2","explanation":"Ruth was a Moabitess -- she was from the country of Moab! Even though she wasn't born an Israelite, she chose to follow the God of Israel. God doesn't care where you come from -- He cares about your heart!"},{"id":145,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What specific greeting did Boaz use when he came from Bethlehem to his reapers in the field?","options":["\"Peace be with you!\"","\"The Lord bless you!\"","\"The Lord be with you!\"","\"God's grace upon you!\""],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 2:4","explanation":"Boaz said 'The Lord be with you!' to his workers, and they answered 'The Lord bless you!' What a wonderful boss! You can tell a lot about a person by how they greet the people who work for them."},{"id":146,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Boaz told Ruth to stay close to whom while gleaning in his fields?","options":["His male servants","His young women","The other foreigners","The field overseers"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:8","explanation":"Boaz told Ruth to stay close to his young women for safety. He also told his young men not to touch her! Boaz was a true gentleman who made sure Ruth was protected while she worked."},{"id":147,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Boaz tell Ruth to do when she was thirsty?","options":["Go to the well in town","Drink from the vessels which the young men have drawn","Ask Naomi for water","Wait until the midday break"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:9","explanation":"Boaz said Ruth could drink from the water his young men had drawn! She didn't even have to do the hard work of drawing water herself. Boaz was already going above and beyond to take care of Ruth!"},{"id":148,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Boaz, what specific things had he been told about Ruth's kindness to Naomi?","options":["That she cooked for Naomi every day","That she left her father, mother, and the land of her birth to come to a people she did not know before","That she sold all her possessions to support Naomi","That she promised to never leave Bethlehem"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:11","explanation":"Boaz knew all about Ruth's sacrifice! She left her own parents and her homeland to follow Naomi to a strange country. That kind of loyalty really impressed Boaz -- and it shows us what true love looks like!"},{"id":149,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"At mealtime, what food did Boaz offer Ruth to eat along with bread?","options":["Honey and figs","Vinegar to dip her bread in","Olives and cheese","Wine and dates"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:14","explanation":"Boaz invited Ruth to come dip her bread in the vinegar! Vinegar (sour wine) was a common refreshing drink for workers in Bible times. He also passed parched grain to her. Boaz made sure Ruth was well fed!"},{"id":150,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What food did Boaz hand to Ruth at mealtime, of which she ate and was satisfied and had some left over?","options":["Bread and honey","Parched grain","Figs and dates","Lentil stew"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 2:14","explanation":"Boaz gave Ruth parched grain -- roasted grain that was a popular snack for field workers! She ate until she was full and still had leftovers. She even brought the leftovers home to Naomi. Sharing is caring!"},{"id":151,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"How much barley did Boaz give Ruth at the threshing floor before she returned to Naomi?","options":["An ephah of barley","Four measures of barley","Six ephahs of barley","Six measures of barley"],"correct":3,"reference":"Ruth 3:15","explanation":"Boaz measured out six measures of barley and put it on Ruth! That was a very generous gift. When Naomi saw it, she knew Boaz meant business and wouldn't rest until the matter was settled!"},{"id":152,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Ruth 4:1, how did Boaz address the closer relative (kinsman-redeemer) who had first right?","options":["\"Brother\"","\"My lord\"","\"Friend\"","\"Kinsman\""],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:1","explanation":"Boaz called him 'Friend' -- or in some NKJV editions a similar term meaning 'such a one.' The Bible never actually tells us this man's real name! He missed out on being in the family line of Jesus because he refused to redeem Ruth."},{"id":153,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What blessing did the elders and people at the gate speak over Boaz regarding Rachel and Leah?","options":["\"May Ruth be as beautiful as Rachel and Leah\"","\"May the Lord make Ruth like Rachel and Leah, the two who built the house of Israel\"","\"May your household be as great as Rachel and Leah's\"","\"May Ruth bear as many children as Rachel and Leah\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:11","explanation":"The people blessed Ruth by comparing her to Rachel and Leah, the two wives of Jacob who built the whole house of Israel! That's an incredible blessing -- and it totally came true because Ruth became the great-grandmother of King David!"},{"id":154,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"In the blessing at the gate, whose house did the elders say they hoped Boaz's house would be like through the offspring the Lord would give?","options":["The house of Abraham","The house of Jacob","The house of Perez, whom Tamar bore to Judah","The house of Moses"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:12","explanation":"They mentioned Perez, who was the son of Tamar and Judah! This is cool because Perez is actually in the family line that leads all the way from Judah to Boaz to David to Jesus!"},{"id":155,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who became the nurse to baby Obed after he was born?","options":["Ruth","Orpah","Naomi","A hired servant"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:16","explanation":"Naomi took the baby Obed and became his nurse! After losing her husband and two sons, God gave Naomi a precious grandchild to hold. The neighbor women said 'A son has been born to Naomi!' How beautiful!"},{"id":156,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to the genealogy at the end of Ruth chapter 4, who was the father of Boaz?","options":["Nahshon","Salmon","Ram","Amminadab"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:21","explanation":"Salmon was the father of Boaz! The genealogy goes: Perez, Hezron, Ram, Amminadab, Nahshon, Salmon, Boaz, Obed, Jesse, David. That's ten generations leading to the greatest king of Israel!"},{"id":157,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"The genealogy at the end of Ruth leads to which famous king of Israel?","options":["King Saul","King Solomon","King David","King Josiah"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:22","explanation":"The whole book of Ruth leads up to King David! Ruth was David's great-grandmother. And it gets even more amazing -- this family line goes all the way to Jesus! God had an incredible plan all along!"},{"id":158,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"hard","question":"In the genealogy of Ruth 4:18-22, who was the father of Nahshon?","options":["Ram","Hezron","Amminadab","Salmon"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 4:19-20","explanation":"Amminadab was the father of Nahshon! Nahshon was actually a very important leader of the tribe of Judah during the time of Moses. God was weaving an amazing family story through all these generations!"},{"id":159,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"easy","question":"At the beginning of the book of Ruth, during whose time did the events take place?","options":["In the days when the kings ruled","In the days when the prophets spoke","In the days when the judges ruled","In the days when Moses led Israel"],"correct":2,"reference":"Ruth 1:1","explanation":"The story of Ruth happened during the time of the judges! This was a pretty wild and sometimes dark period in Israel's history, but God was still working behind the scenes through ordinary people like Ruth and Boaz."},{"id":160,"category":"ruth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did the women of Bethlehem say about Ruth's value to Naomi?","options":["That Ruth was worth more than ten daughters","That Ruth was better to Naomi than seven sons","That Ruth was the greatest woman in Moab","That Ruth was equal to five daughters of Israel"],"correct":1,"reference":"Ruth 4:15","explanation":"The women said Ruth was better to Naomi than seven sons! In those days, sons were considered the most valuable family members, so saying Ruth was worth more than seven sons was the highest compliment possible!"},{"id":161,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to 1 Samuel 1:1, what was the name of Elkanah's father?","options":["Zuph","Tohu","Jeroham","Elihu"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:1","explanation":"Elkanah's father was Jeroham! The verse gives us his whole family tree: Elkanah son of Jeroham, son of Elihu, son of Tohu, son of Zuph. That's four generations of names to remember!"},{"id":162,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"From what place was Elkanah, Hannah's husband?","options":["Bethlehem of Judah","Ramathaim Zophim, of the mountains of Ephraim","Shiloh of Benjamin","Gibeah of Ephraim"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:1","explanation":"Elkanah was from Ramathaim Zophim in the mountains of Ephraim! That's quite a mouthful of a hometown name. This is the same area that later became known simply as Ramah."},{"id":163,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"The Bible says Hannah prayed to the Lord in what emotional state?","options":["In great fear","In bitterness of soul","In overwhelming joy","In quiet peace"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:10","explanation":"Hannah prayed in bitterness of soul and wept in anguish! She was deeply heartbroken about not having children. But here's the beautiful part -- God heard every single tear and every single prayer!"},{"id":164,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Where was Eli the priest sitting when he watched Hannah praying?","options":["At the altar","By the doorpost of the tabernacle","On the steps of the temple","In the inner court"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:9","explanation":"Eli was sitting on a seat by the doorpost of the tabernacle of the Lord! From that spot he could see Hannah's lips moving but couldn't hear any words, which is why he mistakenly thought she was drunk."},{"id":165,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"After Hannah explained herself to Eli, what were his exact words of blessing to her?","options":["\"May God bless you abundantly\"","\"Go in peace, and the God of Israel grant your petition which you have asked of Him\"","\"The Lord hear your prayer and give you a son\"","\"Be at peace, for the Lord has heard you\""],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:17","explanation":"Eli said 'Go in peace, and the God of Israel grant your petition which you have asked of Him.' What powerful words! And guess what -- God did exactly that! Sometimes a word of encouragement can change everything."},{"id":166,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"According to 1 Samuel 1:19, what happened after Elkanah and Hannah returned home from worshipping at Shiloh?","options":["Hannah continued to fast and pray","Elkanah knew Hannah his wife, and the Lord remembered her","They offered another sacrifice to God","Hannah made a second vow to the Lord"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:19-20","explanation":"The Bible says Elkanah knew his wife Hannah, and the Lord remembered her! 'Remembered' doesn't mean God forgot -- it means He acted on her prayer at just the right time. And soon baby Samuel was on the way!"},{"id":167,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to 1 Samuel 1:24 (NKJV), what specific offerings did Hannah bring when she took young Samuel to the house of the Lord at Shiloh?","options":["Two bulls, an ephah of flour, and a skin of wine","Three bulls, one ephah of flour, and a skin of wine","One bull, two ephahs of flour, and two skins of wine","Three lambs, one ephah of flour, and a skin of wine"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:24","explanation":"Hannah brought three bulls, one ephah of flour, and a skin of wine! That was a generous offering showing how serious and thankful she was. She didn't hold anything back when giving her son to God's service."},{"id":168,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"In Hannah's prayer in 1 Samuel 2, she says 'my heart rejoices in the Lord.' What else does she say is exalted?","options":["My soul","My spirit","My horn","My voice"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:1","explanation":"Hannah said 'my horn is exalted in the Lord!' In Bible times, a horn was a symbol of strength and power. Hannah was saying that God had made her strong! He turned her sadness into an amazing victory song!"},{"id":169,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In Hannah's prayer, what does she say will happen to the adversaries of the Lord?","options":["They shall be cast into darkness","They shall be broken in pieces","They shall flee from His presence","They shall be consumed by fire"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:10","explanation":"Hannah declared that 'the adversaries of the Lord shall be broken in pieces!' That's powerful! Hannah's prayer went from being about her personal situation to declaring God's power over all His enemies!"},{"id":170,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"In Hannah's prayer in 1 Samuel 2:9, what does she say God will do for His saints?","options":["He will lift them up on high","He will guard the feet of His saints","He will shelter them under His wings","He will lead them beside still waters"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:9","explanation":"Hannah said God will guard the feet of His saints! That means God watches over every step His people take. He protects them on their journey through life. What a comforting promise!"},{"id":171,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Hannah's prayer in 1 Samuel 2:9, by what shall no man prevail?","options":["By wisdom","By riches","By strength","By might"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:9","explanation":"Hannah said 'by strength shall no man prevail!' This means human muscle and power are nothing compared to God's might. Hannah learned this firsthand -- no human effort could give her a baby, but God could!"},{"id":172,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"medium","question":"At the very end of Hannah's prayer, what two things does she say the Lord will do?","options":["Save His people and defeat all nations","Judge the ends of the earth and give strength to His king and exalt the horn of His anointed","Raise the dead and heal the sick","Open the heavens and pour out blessings"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 2:10","explanation":"Hannah's prayer ends with a prophecy! She said God would judge the ends of the earth, give strength to His king, and exalt His anointed. Amazing -- Israel didn't even have a king yet, but Hannah prophesied about one!"},{"id":173,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"In 1 Samuel 1:11, when Hannah made her vow, what did she promise would never come upon her son's head?","options":["A crown","Water","A razor","Oil"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:11","explanation":"Hannah promised that no razor would ever touch Samuel's head! This was part of dedicating him as a Nazirite to the Lord, meaning he would be set apart for God's special service his entire life."},{"id":174,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What is the name of Elkanah's grandfather according to 1 Samuel 1:1?","options":["Zuph","Jeroham","Elihu","Tohu"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:1","explanation":"Elkanah's grandfather was Elihu! The family line goes: Zuph was the great-grandfather, then Tohu, then Elihu, then Jeroham (the father), and finally Elkanah. That's a lot of family history in just one verse!"},{"id":175,"category":"hannah","difficulty":"easy","question":"According to 1 Samuel 1:13, what was unusual about the way Hannah prayed that confused Eli?","options":["She was lying on the ground","She spoke in her heart; only her lips moved, but her voice was not heard","She was praying with her eyes open","She was dancing while she prayed"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 1:13","explanation":"Hannah spoke in her heart -- her lips were moving but no sound came out! Eli saw this and thought she was drunk, but she was actually praying so deeply and personally that only God could hear her words. What a powerful prayer!"},{"id":250,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"Whose death is recorded at the very beginning of 1 Samuel 25?","options":["King Saul","Samuel","Jonathan","Jesse"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:1","explanation":"Samuel the prophet died and all Israel gathered together to mourn for him. He was buried at his home in Ramah. Samuel was a very important leader in Israel who anointed both Saul and David as kings!"},{"id":251,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"After Samuel's death, where did David go?","options":["The Wilderness of Beersheba","The Wilderness of Paran","The Wilderness of Sinai","The Wilderness of Judah"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:1","explanation":"David went down to the Wilderness of Paran. This was a big desert area in the south. David was still running from King Saul, so he had to keep moving to stay safe!"},{"id":252,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"Nabal was a descendant of which famous Old Testament figure?","options":["Abraham","Moses","Caleb","Joshua"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:3","explanation":"Nabal was of the house of Caleb! Caleb was one of the two faithful spies who trusted God when Israel first came to the Promised Land. Too bad Nabal didn't inherit Caleb's good attitude!"},{"id":253,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"What was Nabal doing in Carmel when David sent his young men?","options":["Building a house","Having a wedding feast","Shearing his sheep","Planting a vineyard"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:2,4","explanation":"Nabal was shearing his sheep in Carmel. Sheep-shearing time was like a harvest festival -- a time of celebration and generosity. That's why David thought it was a good time to ask for provisions!"},{"id":254,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What greeting did David instruct his young men to give Nabal?","options":["\"Grace and mercy to you\"","\"Peace be to you, peace to your house, and peace to all that you have\"","\"The Lord bless you and keep you\"","\"May the Lord be with your spirit\""],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:6","explanation":"David told his men to say 'Peace be to you, peace to your house, and peace to all that you have!' That's a triple peace blessing! David was being super polite and respectful to Nabal."},{"id":255,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"David told his young men to go to Nabal and greet him in whose name?","options":["In the name of the Lord","In David's name","In the name of King Saul","In the name of Samuel"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:5,9","explanation":"David told the young men to greet Nabal 'in my name' -- that is, in David's name. This was a formal and respectful way to make the request. David wanted Nabal to know exactly who was asking!"},{"id":256,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"How many of David's men stayed behind with the supplies while 400 went to fight Nabal?","options":["100","150","200","250"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:13","explanation":"Two hundred men stayed with the supplies while 400 went with David. That means David had about 600 men total! Somebody had to guard all their stuff while the rest went on the mission."},{"id":257,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"Did Abigail tell Nabal she was going to meet David with provisions?","options":["Yes, she told him everything","Yes, but only after she packed the donkeys","No, she told him nothing","She sent a servant to tell him later"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:19","explanation":"Abigail did NOT tell her husband Nabal! The Bible says she told her servants to go ahead and she would follow, 'but she did not tell her husband Nabal.' She knew he would have stopped her wise plan!"},{"id":258,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"easy","question":"What animal did Abigail ride when she went to meet David?","options":["A horse","A camel","A donkey","A mule"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:20","explanation":"Abigail rode on a donkey as she went down under cover of the hill to meet David. Donkeys were very common for travel in Bible times, and they were great for going through rocky, hilly paths!"},{"id":259,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"What oath did Abigail use when she spoke to David, beginning with what phrase?","options":["\"By the name of the Lord God of Israel\"","\"As the Lord lives and as your soul lives\"","\"As surely as the sun rises\"","\"By the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob\""],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:26","explanation":"Abigail said 'As the LORD lives and as your soul lives.' This was a very serious oath in Bible times! Abigail was making a solemn promise to David, showing how seriously she took the whole situation."},{"id":260,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"Abigail told David that his life would be 'bound in the bundle of the living with the LORD your God.' What did she say would happen to his enemies' lives?","options":["They would be scattered like dust","They would be cut off from the land","God would sling them out as from the pocket of a sling","They would melt like wax before fire"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:29","explanation":"Abigail said God would 'sling out' the lives of David's enemies, 'as from the pocket of a sling!' This was a clever reference to how David defeated Goliath with a sling. Abigail was one smart lady!"},{"id":261,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"What request did Abigail make of David for the future?","options":["That he would spare Nabal's life","That he would protect her household","That he would remember her when the Lord dealt well with him","That he would make peace with King Saul"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:31","explanation":"Abigail asked David to remember her when God blessed him. She could see that David would become a great leader one day! And sure enough, David did remember her and later sent for her to be his wife."},{"id":262,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"Approximately how many days after Nabal's feast did the Lord strike him and he died?","options":["About 3 days","About 7 days","About 10 days","About 14 days"],"correct":2,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:38","explanation":"It was about ten days later that the Lord struck Nabal and he died. First his heart 'died within him and he became like a stone,' and then about ten days after that, the Lord struck him. God took care of the situation in His own time!"},{"id":263,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"medium","question":"After Nabal died, how did David propose to Abigail?","options":["He went to her house personally","He sent his servants to her to propose marriage","He sent a letter through a messenger","He met her at the well in the city"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:39-40","explanation":"David sent servants to Abigail to speak to her and propose marriage on his behalf. When Abigail heard David's proposal, she bowed down and quickly got ready to go with his servants. What a love story!"},{"id":264,"category":"abigail","difficulty":"hard","question":"In 1 Samuel 25:3, what two qualities are specifically used to describe Abigail alongside her connection to Nabal?","options":["Righteous and faithful","Good understanding and beautiful appearance","Gentle and humble in spirit","Wise in heart and gracious in speech"],"correct":1,"reference":"1 Samuel 25:3","explanation":"The Bible says Abigail was 'a woman of good understanding and beautiful appearance.' She had both brains AND beauty! The verse then contrasts her with Nabal who was 'harsh and evil in his doings.' What a difference between husband and wife!"},{"id":265,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Why did the Lord allow the Canaanites to oppress Israel before Deborah became judge?","options":["Israel forgot to tithe","The children of Israel did evil in the sight of the Lord","Israel made a treaty with Egypt","Israel stopped going to the tabernacle"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:1","explanation":"The children of Israel again did evil in the sight of the Lord! This is a pattern you see again and again in Judges -- Israel sins, God allows an enemy to oppress them, they cry out to God, and God raises up a judge to save them."},{"id":266,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"Which judge had died before Deborah's story begins in Judges 4?","options":["Othniel","Shamgar","Ehud","Gideon"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:1","explanation":"Ehud had died before the events of Judges 4. Ehud was the left-handed judge who defeated King Eglon of Moab. After Ehud died, Israel went back to doing evil, and that's when God allowed King Jabin to oppress them."},{"id":267,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What was the name of the city where Sisera, the commander of Jabin's army, dwelt?","options":["Hazor","Harosheth Hagoyim","Megiddo","Taanach"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:2","explanation":"Sisera dwelt in Harosheth Hagoyim, which means 'Harosheth of the Gentiles.' That's quite a fancy name for a city! Sisera was the powerful commander of King Jabin's army with all those 900 iron chariots."},{"id":268,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did Deborah summon Barak to come to her?","options":["She traveled to his city","She sent and called for him","He came on his own to seek advice","She called out to him from her palm tree"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:6","explanation":"Deborah SENT and called for Barak son of Abinoam from Kedesh in Naphtali. She didn't go to him -- she summoned him! That shows how much authority Deborah had as a judge and prophetess in Israel."},{"id":269,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Deborah say to Barak when she gave him God's command? She began with which phrase?","options":["\"Thus says the Lord God of Israel\"","\"Has not the Lord God of Israel commanded\"","\"Hear the word of the Lord\"","\"The Lord your God says to you\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:6","explanation":"Deborah said, 'Has not the LORD God of Israel commanded?' She was reminding Barak that this wasn't just her idea -- it was GOD's command! Deborah spoke with the full authority of God's word."},{"id":270,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Which two tribes did Deborah specifically tell Barak to gather men from?","options":["Judah and Benjamin","Naphtali and Zebulun","Ephraim and Manasseh","Dan and Asher"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:6","explanation":"Deborah told Barak to take men from the tribes of Naphtali and Zebulun. These were tribes in the northern part of Israel, right near where the battle would take place. God had a specific plan for which soldiers to use!"},{"id":271,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Where did Deborah tell Barak to gather the 10,000 men?","options":["Mount Sinai","Mount Carmel","Mount Tabor","Mount Hermon"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:6","explanation":"Mount Tabor was the gathering place! It's a big mountain in northern Israel that rises up from a flat valley. It was a great strategic location because from up there, you could see the enemy coming from far away."},{"id":272,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"According to Judges 4:15, what did the Lord do to Sisera and his army?","options":["The Lord confused them","The Lord routed Sisera and all his chariots and all his army","The Lord sent fire from heaven","The Lord caused an earthquake"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:15","explanation":"The LORD routed Sisera and all his chariots and army with the edge of the sword before Barak. 'Routed' means He threw them into total panic and confusion! God did the real fighting -- Barak and his men just had to show up and be brave."},{"id":273,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"After the Lord routed his army, what did Sisera do?","options":["He surrendered to Barak","He fled to King Jabin","He alighted from his chariot and fled away on foot","He hid among the dead soldiers"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 4:15","explanation":"Sisera jumped down from his chariot and ran away on foot! Imagine that -- the mighty commander of 900 iron chariots was so terrified that he abandoned his own chariot and ran! That's what happens when God fights the battle."},{"id":274,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What exact words did Jael say to invite Sisera into her tent?","options":["\"Come in, come in, do not be afraid\"","\"Turn aside, my lord, turn aside to me; do not fear\"","\"Enter and rest, my lord, for you are safe here\"","\"Welcome, my lord, come and hide yourself\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:18","explanation":"Jael said, 'Turn aside, my lord, turn aside to me; do not fear.' She sounded so welcoming and reassuring! Sisera thought he was going to a safe hiding place, but God had a very different plan in store for him."},{"id":275,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"What did Jael use to cover Sisera when he lay down in her tent?","options":["A blanket","A rug","A cloak","Animal skins"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:18","explanation":"Jael covered Sisera with a rug (some translations say blanket). She was making him feel safe and comfortable so he would fall asleep. Sisera was exhausted from running and thought he had found a perfect hiding spot!"},{"id":276,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did Sisera ask Jael for to drink?","options":["A cup of wine","A little water","Some goat's milk","A bowl of broth"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:19","explanation":"Sisera asked Jael, 'Please give me a little water to drink, for I am thirsty.' But Jael did even better -- she opened a jug of milk and gave him a drink instead! Then she covered him up again. She was being extra hospitable before her big move!"},{"id":277,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"After Jael defeated Sisera, who came pursuing him, and what did Jael do?","options":["David came, and Jael hid","Barak came, and Jael went out to show him Sisera","Joshua came, and Jael told him the news","Gideon came, and Jael called to him"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 4:22","explanation":"Barak came in pursuit of Sisera, and Jael went out to meet him and said, 'Come, I will show you the man whom you seek.' When Barak went in, he found Sisera lying dead! Deborah's prophecy came true -- the glory went to a woman, not to Barak."},{"id":278,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"easy","question":"Who sang the victory song together in Judges chapter 5?","options":["Barak and Jael","Deborah and Jael","Deborah and Barak","All the people of Israel"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 5:1","explanation":"Deborah and Barak sang together on that day! Their song is one of the most famous victory songs in the entire Bible. It praises God for the amazing victory He gave Israel over Sisera and his powerful army."},{"id":279,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In the Song of Deborah, what place is mentioned in the phrase 'Lord, when You went out from Seir, when You marched from the field of Edom'?","options":["Mount Sinai","Seir and Edom","Egypt and the Red Sea","Jordan and Jericho"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:4","explanation":"The song says 'LORD, when You went out from Seir, when You marched from the field of Edom.' Seir and Edom refer to the same region south of Israel. The song is remembering how God powerfully led His people from the very beginning!"},{"id":280,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"What is the exact repeated rallying cry directed at Deborah in Judges 5:12?","options":["\"Rise up, rise up, Deborah! Rise up and lead!\"","\"Be strong, be strong, Deborah! Be strong and courageous!\"","\"Awake, awake, Deborah! Awake, awake, sing a song!\"","\"Stand firm, stand firm, Deborah! Stand firm in the Lord!\""],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 5:12","explanation":"The song cries out, 'Awake, awake, Deborah! Awake, awake, sing a song!' The word 'awake' is repeated four times! It's like an excited cheer rallying Deborah to rise up and celebrate what God has done. How exciting!"},{"id":281,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"hard","question":"In the Song of Deborah, which tribes are criticized for NOT coming to fight in the battle?","options":["Judah, Simeon, and Levi","Reuben, Dan, and Asher","Ephraim, Manasseh, and Benjamin","Gad, Issachar, and Naphtali"],"correct":1,"reference":"Judges 5:15-17","explanation":"Reuben, Dan, and Asher are called out for staying behind! Reuben stayed with their sheep, Dan remained on their ships, and Asher stayed by the seashore. When God calls you to action, you don't want to be the one who stayed home!"},{"id":282,"category":"deborah","difficulty":"medium","question":"In Judges 5, who is described as looking through a window, waiting and wondering?","options":["Deborah","Jael","The mother of Sisera","The wife of Barak"],"correct":2,"reference":"Judges 5:28","explanation":"The mother of Sisera looked through the window and cried out, wondering where her son was. She kept waiting for his chariot to come home. It's a sad picture -- she didn't know her son would never return from the battle."},{"id":283,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Zacharias the priest belonged to which priestly division?","options":["The division of Zadok","The division of Abijah","The division of Ithamar","The division of Eleazar"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:5","explanation":"Zacharias was of the division of Abijah. King David had organized the priests into 24 divisions for serving in the temple, and Abijah's division was the eighth one. Each division took turns serving in the temple!"},{"id":284,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Which king was ruling when the story of Zacharias and Elizabeth begins?","options":["King Augustus","King Herod","King Archelaus","King Agrippa"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:5","explanation":"It was 'in the days of Herod, the king of Judea.' This was Herod the Great, who was known for being a very cruel king. But even in dark times under a bad king, God was working out His amazing plan!"},{"id":285,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How does Luke 1:6 describe Zacharias and Elizabeth's character?","options":["They were wealthy and generous","They were righteous before God, walking blameless in all the commandments","They were humble and poor in spirit","They were faithful in tithing and prayer"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:6","explanation":"They were 'both righteous before God, walking in all the commandments and ordinances of the Lord blameless.' What an amazing description! They truly loved God and obeyed His laws with all their hearts."},{"id":286,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Why did Zacharias and Elizabeth have no children?","options":["They were too young","Elizabeth was barren","They had not been married long","They chose not to have children"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:7","explanation":"Elizabeth was barren, which means she couldn't have children, and they were both well advanced in years. But God loves to do the impossible! Just like He did with Sarah and Hannah, God had a miracle baby planned for Elizabeth too."},{"id":287,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How was Zacharias chosen to burn incense in the temple?","options":["The high priest selected him","His lot fell to burn incense","He volunteered for the duty","He was next in the rotation schedule"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:9","explanation":"His lot fell to burn incense! The priests cast lots (like drawing straws) to decide who would do this special job. A priest might only get this honor once in his lifetime, so this was a HUGE deal for Zacharias!"},{"id":288,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What were the first words the angel Gabriel said to Zacharias?","options":["\"Greetings, chosen one\"","\"Peace be with you, Zacharias\"","\"Do not be afraid, Zacharias\"","\"Listen carefully, Zacharias\""],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:13","explanation":"Gabriel said, 'Do not be afraid, Zacharias!' Zacharias was troubled and afraid when he saw the angel. 'Do not be afraid' is something angels say a LOT in the Bible -- because seeing an angel is pretty scary!"},{"id":289,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"According to the angel, John would be great in whose sight?","options":["In the sight of all Israel","In the sight of kings and rulers","In the sight of the Lord","In the sight of the nations"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:15","explanation":"John would 'be great in the sight of the Lord.' It doesn't matter if the whole world thinks you're important -- what matters most is being great in GOD's eyes! And John was exactly that."},{"id":290,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"What did the angel say John must never drink?","options":["Water from foreign wells","Neither wine nor strong drink","The cup of the Gentiles","Neither milk nor honey"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:15","explanation":"The angel said John 'shall drink neither wine nor strong drink.' This was similar to a Nazirite vow, showing that John was set apart for God's special purpose from before he was even born! He was dedicated completely to God."},{"id":291,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"From when would John be filled with the Holy Spirit, according to the angel?","options":["From his baptism","From the day of his circumcision","Even from his mother's womb","From the age of accountability"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:15","explanation":"John would be 'filled with the Holy Spirit, even from his mother's womb!' That's incredible -- filled with God's Spirit before he was even born! We already saw this happen when baby John leaped in Elizabeth's womb when Mary visited."},{"id":292,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"The angel said John would go before the Lord in the spirit and power of which Old Testament prophet?","options":["Moses","Isaiah","Elijah","Jeremiah"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:17","explanation":"John would go in 'the spirit and power of Elijah!' Just like Elijah boldly called Israel to repent, John the Baptist would do the same thing. He would prepare the way for Jesus by turning people's hearts back to God."},{"id":293,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Luke 1:17, what was John's mission described as?","options":["To baptize all of Israel","To make ready a people prepared for the Lord","To rebuild the temple of God","To restore the kingdom to Israel"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:17","explanation":"John's mission was 'to make ready a people prepared for the Lord.' He was like an advance team getting everything ready before the King arrives! John's whole life purpose was to prepare people's hearts for Jesus."},{"id":294,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"When Zacharias asked how he could be sure of the angel's message, what did Gabriel say about himself?","options":["\"I am a messenger of the Most High\"","\"I am Gabriel, who stands in the presence of God\"","\"I am sent from the throne of heaven\"","\"I am the angel of the Lord Almighty\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:19","explanation":"Gabriel said, 'I am Gabriel, who stands in the presence of God!' Wow -- Gabriel actually stands right in the presence of God Himself! When an angel like that brings you a message, you'd better believe it. Poor Zacharias learned that the hard way!"},{"id":295,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"Where was the angel sent to visit Mary?","options":["To Bethlehem in Judea","To Jerusalem in Judea","To Nazareth, a city of Galilee","To Capernaum by the Sea of Galilee"],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:26","explanation":"Gabriel was sent to Nazareth, a city of Galilee. Nazareth was a small, unimportant town -- people even said 'Can anything good come out of Nazareth?' But God chose this humble place for the most amazing announcement in history!"},{"id":296,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"What were Gabriel's exact first words to Mary in the NKJV?","options":["\"Hail Mary, full of grace, the Lord is with you\"","\"Rejoice, highly favored one, the Lord is with you\"","\"Greetings, blessed one, the Lord has chosen you\"","\"Peace to you, favored daughter of Israel\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:28","explanation":"Gabriel said, 'Rejoice, highly favored one, the Lord is with you; blessed are you among women!' What an amazing greeting! Mary was chosen by God out of all the women in the world for the most special job ever."},{"id":297,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"According to Luke 1:35, how did the angel describe what would happen to Mary? Complete: 'The Holy Spirit will come upon you, and the power of the _____ will overshadow you.'","options":["Most High","Highest","Almighty","Lord God"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:35","explanation":"The NKJV says 'the power of the Highest will overshadow you.' This was how God would perform the miracle of Jesus being born -- through the power of the Holy Spirit and the Highest (God Himself). It was a one-of-a-kind miracle!"},{"id":298,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"What famous phrase did the angel say to Mary about God's power?","options":["\"God can do all things\"","\"Nothing is too hard for God\"","\"With God nothing will be impossible\"","\"The arm of the Lord is not shortened\""],"correct":2,"reference":"Luke 1:37","explanation":"'For with God nothing will be impossible!' This is one of the most encouraging verses in the whole Bible. No matter how big your problem seems, remember -- NOTHING is impossible with God. He can do anything!"},{"id":299,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"What was Mary's response to the angel's message about becoming the mother of Jesus?","options":["\"I will do as you say, my lord\"","\"Let it be to me according to your word\"","\"May the will of God be done\"","\"I accept this with a grateful heart\""],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:38","explanation":"Mary said, 'Behold the maidservant of the Lord! Let it be to me according to your word.' What incredible faith and humility! Mary didn't argue or question anymore -- she simply trusted God and said YES to His plan."},{"id":300,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"medium","question":"How did Mary travel to visit Elizabeth after the angel's announcement?","options":["She went slowly with a caravan","She arose and went with haste into the hill country to a city of Judah","She waited a month then journeyed south","She traveled by donkey with Joseph"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:39","explanation":"Mary 'arose in those days and went with haste into the hill country, to a city of Judah.' She didn't waste any time -- she hurried to see her cousin Elizabeth! Mary was so excited about what God was doing that she rushed to share it."},{"id":301,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"hard","question":"At the cross, what were Jesus's exact words to Mary about the beloved disciple?","options":["\"Mother, this is now your son\"","\"Woman, behold your son!\"","\"Dear mother, he will care for you\"","\"Woman, this disciple will be your son\""],"correct":1,"reference":"John 19:26","explanation":"Jesus said, 'Woman, behold your son!' Even while suffering on the cross, Jesus cared about His mother's future. He made sure she would be taken care of by the disciple He loved. What an amazing example of love and responsibility!"},{"id":302,"category":"mary_elizabeth","difficulty":"easy","question":"Mary was betrothed (engaged) to which man when the angel Gabriel visited her?","options":["Zacharias","Joseph","Simeon","James"],"correct":1,"reference":"Luke 1:27","explanation":"Mary was betrothed to a man named Joseph, who was of the house of David. Being betrothed was like being engaged but even more serious in Bible times. God chose Joseph to be the earthly father who would help raise baby Jesus!"}];
